Cloud password spray from a specific IP — SigninLogs
This shows the spray pattern from 8.8.8.8: many users, low tries per user, lots of failures (and any successes).

let sprayIP = "8.8.8.8";
let lookback = 24h;
let binSize = 15m;

// Tune
let minAccounts = 10;
let maxPerAccount = 3;
let minTotalFails = 20;

let perAccount =
SigninLogs
| where TimeGenerated > ago(lookback)
| where isnotempty(UserPrincipalName) and isnotempty(IPAddress)
| where IPAddress == sprayIP
| summarize Attempts=count(),
            Fails=countif(ResultType != 0),
            Success=countif(ResultType == 0),
            Apps=make_set(AppDisplayName, 5),
            Clients=make_set(ClientAppUsed, 5),
            ResultDescs=make_set(ResultDescription, 5),
            FirstSeen=min(TimeGenerated),
            LastSeen=max(TimeGenerated)
  by bin(TimeGenerated, binSize), IPAddress, UserPrincipalName;

perAccount
| where Fails > 0
| where Attempts between (1 .. maxPerAccount)
| summarize
    AccountsTargeted=dcount(UserPrincipalName),
    TotalFails=sum(Fails),
    TotalSuccess=sum(Success),
    SampleAccounts=make_set(UserPrincipalName, 25),
    SampleApps=make_set(tostring(Apps), 10),
    SampleClients=make_set(tostring(Clients), 10),
    SampleFailReasons=make_set(tostring(ResultDescs), 10),
    FirstSeen=min(FirstSeen),
    LastSeen=max(LastSeen)
  by TimeGenerated, IPAddress
| where AccountsTargeted >= minAccounts and TotalFails >= minTotalFails
| order by AccountsTargeted desc, TotalFails desc, TimeGenerated desc



On-prem style password spray from a specific IP — IdentityLogonEvents
This detects the same pattern from 8.8.8.8, and includes failure reasons like wrong password/locked.

let sprayIP = "8.8.8.8";
let lookback = 24h;
let binSize = 15m;

// Tune
let minAccounts = 10;
let maxPerAccount = 3;
let minTotalFails = 20;
let excludeComputerAccounts = true;

let perAccount =
IdentityLogonEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(lookback)
| extend Account=tostring(AccountName),
         SrcIP=tostring(IPAddress),
         SrcDevice=tostring(DeviceName),
         Reason=tostring(FailureReason),
         Proto=tostring(Protocol),
         Action=tostring(ActionType)
| where SrcIP == sprayIP
| where isnotempty(Account)
| where excludeComputerAccounts == false or Account !endswith "$"
| summarize Attempts=count(),
            Fails=countif(Action has "Fail" or Reason has_any ("wrong","bad","invalid","locked")),
            Success=countif(Action has "Success"),
            Reasons=make_set(Reason, 5),
            Protocols=make_set(Proto, 5),
            FirstSeen=min(TimeGenerated),
            LastSeen=max(TimeGenerated)
  by bin(TimeGenerated, binSize), SrcIP, SrcDevice, Account;

perAccount
| where Fails > 0
| where Attempts between (1 .. maxPerAccount)
| summarize
    AccountsTargeted=dcount(Account),
    TotalFails=sum(Fails),
    TotalSuccess=sum(Success),
    SampleAccounts=make_set(Account, 25),
    SampleReasons=make_set(tostring(Reasons), 10),
    SampleProtocols=make_set(tostring(Protocols), 10),
    FirstSeen=min(FirstSeen),
    LastSeen=max(LastSeen)
  by TimeGenerated, SrcIP, SrcDevice
| where AccountsTargeted >= minAccounts and TotalFails >= minTotalFails
| order by AccountsTargeted desc, TotalFails desc, TimeGenerated desc


URL From Email check: 

The "Simple" Trace Query 
This query finds clicks on a specific suspicious URL and joins them with the corresponding email logs to show you who sent it and what the subject was.

UrlClickEvents
| where Url has "suspicious-link.com" // Replace with the link you're investigating
| join kind=inner (EmailEvents) on NetworkMessageId
| project ClickTime=Timestamp, SenderFromAddress, Subject, RecipientEmailAddress, Url, ActionType



Variety: Find the Email via the Recipient 
If you don't have the exact URL but you know which user clicked something suspicious, you can search by their email address:

UrlClickEvents
| where AccountUpn =~ "user@yourdomain.com"
| where Timestamp > ago(24h)
| join kind=inner (EmailEvents) on NetworkMessageId
| project Timestamp, SenderFromAddress, Subject, Url, ActionType
| sort by Timestamp desc




KQL Hunting Query: Potential Pass-the-Hash (PtH), searches for logon type 9 (new credentials). which is the primary inidcator of a PtH attempt using tools like mimikatz, where a local process impersonates a remote user.

SecurityEvent
| where EventID == 4624
| where LogonType == 9 
| where AuthenticationPackageName == "Negotiate" or AuthenticationPackageName == "Kerberos"
| summarize SuccessCount = count() by Computer, Account, IpAddress, LogonTypeName, ProcessName
| order by SuccessCount desc


KQL Hunting Query: Kerberos Encryption Downgrade (PtT). Attachkers often use RC4 encrytion(0x17) for forged or passed tickets because it's easier to crack or manipulate. Modern Windows envrionments should almost exclusively use AES (0x12 or 0x3)

SecurityEvent
| where EventID == 4769 // Kerberos Service Ticket Request
| extend TicketEncryption = tostring(parse_json(EventData).TicketEncryptionType)
| where TicketEncryption == "0x17" // RC4-HMAC (suspicious)
| where Status == "0x0" // Success only
| project TimeGenerated, Computer, TargetUserName, ServiceName, TicketEncryption, IpAddress



KQL: Correlating Logons with Processes (PTH)
This query finds Logons and then "reaches out" to find the process that triggered them.

let LogonEvents = SecurityEvent
| where EventID == 4624
| where LogonType in (9, 3) // Type 9 (NewCredentials/PtH) or Type 3 (Network)
| project LogonTime = TimeGenerated, Computer, Account, TargetLogonId, IpAddress;
SecurityEvent
| where EventID == 4688 // Process Creation
| project ProcessTime = TimeGenerated, Computer, NewProcessName, ParentProcessName, TargetLogonId
| join kind=inner (LogonEvents) on Computer, TargetLogonId
| where NewProcessName !endswith "\\lsass.exe" // Typical FP
| where NewProcessName !endswith "\\VeeamGuestHelper.exe" // Example Backup FP
| project LogonTime, Computer, Account, IpAddress, NewProcessName, ParentProcessName


